(7, 12, 'Som Tum (Thai Green Papaya Salad)', '\"[\\\"green papaya, peeled, seeded, and shredded\\\",\\\"carrots, shredded\\\",\\\"Roma tomatoes, quartered\\\",\\\"Thai chilies, sliced (adjust to your spice preference)\\\",\\\"long beans, cut into 1-inch pieces (optional)\\\",\\\"cloves garlic\\\",\\\"\\\\/4 cup roasted peanuts\\\",\\\"tablespoons fish sauce\\\",\\\"tablespoons lime juice\\\",\\\"tablespoon palm sugar (or brown sugar)\\\",\\\"Optional: Cooked crab or dried shrimp for added flavor\\\",\\\"Add Peanuts: Stir in most of the roasted peanuts, reserving some for garnish.\\\",\\\"Serve: Transfer the Som Tum to a serving plate. Garnish with the remaining roasted peanuts. Serve immediately. Traditionally, it\'s served on a banana leaf.\\\",\\\"Notes:\\\",\\\"The key to a good Som Tum is the balance of sweet, sour, salty, and spicy flavors. Adjust the ingredients in the dressing to your taste.\\\",\\\"Green papaya can be found at Asian markets. If you can\'t find it, you can substitute it with other crunchy vegetables like jicama or green mango.\\\",\\\"Pounding the ingredients in a mortar helps release their flavors and combine them properly. If you don\'t have a mortar, you can use a large bowl and a wooden spoon to gently mix the ingredients.\\\",\\\"For a vegetarian version, omit the fish sauce and use soy sauce or a vegetarian fish sauce substitute.\\\",\\\"If you\'re using cooked crab or dried shrimp, add them to the mortar along with the other vegetables.\\\",\\\"Cabai bubuk\\\"]\"', '\"[\\\"Prepare the Papaya and Vegetables: Peel, seed, and shred the green papaya. Shred the carrots. Quarter the tomatoes. Cut the long beans (if using) into 1-inch pieces.\\\",\\\"Make the Dressing: In a mortar, pound the garlic and chilies into a paste. Add the palm sugar, fish sauce, and lime juice. Mix well until the sugar is dissolved. Taste and adjust the seasoning as needed (more lime juice for sourness, more fish sauce for saltiness, more sugar for sweetness).\\\",\